From: Joey Eamigh <55670930+JoeyEamigh@users.noreply.github.com>
Date: Sun, 01 Jun 2026 00:35:00 -0400
Subject: [PATCH] Input: rotary-encoder - decode by accumulating gray
 transitions

The Car Thing's mechanical encoder bounces hard: measured 200-600 raw
gray-code edges per detent on the transition (the gpio_intc glitch
filter at max only knocks that down ~2.6x). The stock half-period
state machine latches a direction from the last odd intermediate state
and reports it on the next even state, with no validation that the
intermediate was actually traversed - so a bounce that momentarily
reads the opposite neighbour latches and reports the wrong direction.
A time-based report debounce on top of it cannot win: slow detents are
discrete bursts so one report lands per detent, but a fast flick merges
the detents into one continuous bounce storm where the lockout swallows
most of them and a reversal still leaks. Measured: ten fast forward
detents decoded to two forward and one backward event.

Since the board catches every edge of both lines (one gpio_intc
channel per line+polarity), decode by accumulating signed gray-code
transitions instead. Each edge advances the state by one position; the
step direction is (state - last) mod 4 == 1 forward or == 3 backward
(0 = no move, 2 = a missed edge, both ignored). A detent is two gray
steps, so emit one event per two net steps in a direction. Contact
bounce is oscillation between two adjacent states - it accumulates
+1, -1, +1, -1 and nets to zero, never reaching the emit threshold -
so only genuine monotonic rotation produces events. This is immune to
bounce magnitude and never throttles a fast spin: ten forward detents
accumulate twenty net forward steps and emit ten forward events,
whatever the bounce in between.

This replaces the report-debounce approach; the gpio_intc glitch
filter (separate patch) stays as a cheap front-line edge-rate cut, but
correctness no longer depends on it. Only the half-period handler is
reworked - the board selects it via rotary-encoder,steps-per-period=2,
and two gray steps per detent is its calibration (ten slow detents
measured as eleven events under the old decoder).

Signed-off-by: Joey Eamigh <55670930+JoeyEamigh@users.noreply.github.com>
Upstream-Status: Pending
---
 drivers/input/misc/rotary_encoder.c | 25 +++++++++++++++++++------
 1 file changed, 19 insertions(+), 6 deletions(-)

diff --git a/drivers/input/misc/rotary_encoder.c b/drivers/input/misc/rotary_encoder.c
--- a/drivers/input/misc/rotary_encoder.c
+++ b/drivers/input/misc/rotary_encoder.c
@@ -51,6 +51,7 @@
 	signed char dir;	/* 1 - clockwise, -1 - CCW */
 
 	unsigned int last_stable;
+	int accum;
 };
 
 static unsigned int rotary_encoder_get_state(struct rotary_encoder *encoder)
@@ -135,19 +136,31 @@
 static irqreturn_t rotary_encoder_half_period_irq(int irq, void *dev_id)
 {
 	struct rotary_encoder *encoder = dev_id;
-	unsigned int state;
+	unsigned int state, delta;
 
 	guard(mutex)(&encoder->access_mutex);
 
 	state = rotary_encoder_get_state(encoder);
+	delta = (state - encoder->last_stable) & 3;
+	encoder->last_stable = state;
 
-	if (state & 1) {
-		encoder->dir = ((encoder->last_stable - state + 1) % 4) - 1;
-	} else {
-		if (state != encoder->last_stable) {
-			rotary_encoder_report_event(encoder);
-			encoder->last_stable = state;
-		}
+	/* one gray step: 1 forward, 3 back; 0 no move, 2 a missed edge - ignore both */
+	if (delta == 1)
+		encoder->accum++;
+	else if (delta == 3)
+		encoder->accum--;
+	else
+		return IRQ_HANDLED;
+
+	/* a detent is two gray steps; contact bounce oscillates +-1 and nets out below this */
+	if (encoder->accum >= 2) {
+		encoder->accum -= 2;
+		encoder->dir = 1;
+		rotary_encoder_report_event(encoder);
+	} else if (encoder->accum <= -2) {
+		encoder->accum += 2;
+		encoder->dir = -1;
+		rotary_encoder_report_event(encoder);
 	}
 
 	return IRQ_HANDLED;
-- 
